[normal]The House of Lords Economic Affairs committee is running a concurrent inquiry into shale gas to which Cuadrilla has recently submitted evidence. There are some areas of mutual focus in the two inquiries and consequently some of the evidence below 
[normal]has also 
[normal]been provided to the House of Lords committee
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction to Cuadrilla
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Cuadrilla has attracted much media focus on exploration of shale gas in the UK and is proud to be the first-mover in what could prove to be a very economically beneficial industry 
[normal]for the UK. In our view a UK shale gas industry could managed correctly, be instrumental in providing highly skilled jobs in 
[normal]areas which badly need them, building energy security, 
[normal]supplying tax revenues for the exchequer as 
[normal]North Sea revenues diminish, 
[normal]mee
[normal]ting demand for energy for electricity, hea
[normal]ting and industrial use, and in 
[normal]playing an important role in the UK’s future energy mix. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Cuadrilla is a small, specialist, British SME with 
[normal]considerable expertise 
[normal]in geology and unconventional
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]oil and gas engine
[normal]ering and drilling.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] We are in the vanguard of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]unconventional oil and gas exploration in Britain
[normal].
[normal] Together with our partners Centrica and A.J. Lucas we hold a 1200 KM2 
[normal]exploration 
[normal]licence in the Bowland basin in Lancashire.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Cuadrilla plans to drill,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]hydra
[normal]ulically fracture and flow test a small number of exploratory wells to show how much of the huge quantity of natural ga
[normal]s in place in the Bowland shale
[normal] 
[normal]could be 
[normal]commercially recoverable.
